05837nam a22008535i 9780857454591DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2011051803  a97808574545917 a10.1515/97808574545912doi  a(DE-B1597)637488  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aRC450.A9bJ68 2012 4aRC450.A9bJ68 2012eb 7aHIS0400002bisacsh04a362.196/8900943622300aJourneys Into Madness :bMapping Mental Illness in the Austro-Hungarian Empire /ced. by Gemma Blackshaw, Sabine Wieber. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (222 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAustrian and Habsburg Studies ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Figures -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Mad Objects of Fin-de-Siècle Vienna: Journeys, Contexts and Dislocations in the Exhibition ‘Madness and Modernity’ -- t2. Solving Riddles: Freud, Vienna and the Historiography of Madness -- t3. Symphonies and Psychosis in Mahler’s Vienna -- t4. Creating an Appropriate Social Milieu: Journeys to Health at a Sanatorium for Nervous Disorders -- t5. Travel to the Spas: The Growth of Health Tourism in Central Europe, 1850–1914 -- t6. Vienna’s Most Fashionable Neurasthenic: Empress Sisi and the Cult of Size Zero -- t7. Peter Altenberg: Authoring Madness in Vienna circa 1900 -- t8. ‘Hell Is Not Interesting, It Is Terrifying’: A Reading of the Madhouse Chapter in Robert Musil’s The Man without Qualities -- t9. Reason Dazzled: Klimt, Krakauer and the Eyes of the Medusa -- t10. Mapping the Sanatorium: Heinrich Obersteiner and the Art of Psychiatric Patients in Oberdöbling around 1900 -- t11. The Württemberg Asylum of Schussenried: A Psychiatric Space and Its Encounter with Literature and Culture from the ‘Outside’ -- tSelect Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the turn of the century, Sigmund Freud’s investigation of the mind represented a particular journey into mental illness, but it was not the only exploration of this ‘territory’ in the Austro-Hungarian Empire. Sanatoriums were the new tourism destinations, psychiatrists were collecting art works produced by patients and writers were developing innovative literary techniques to convey a character’s interior life. This collection of essays uses the framework of journeys in order to highlight the diverse artistic, cultural and medical responses to a peculiarly Viennese anxiety about the madness of modern times. The travellers of these journeys vary from patients to doctors, artists to writers, architects to composers and royalty to tourists; in engaging with their histories, the contributors reveal the different ways in which madness was experienced and represented in ‘Vienna 1900’.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMedicine in literature. 0aMental health serviceszAustriaxHistory. 0aMental illnesszAustriaxHistory. 0aMentally illzAustriaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Austria & Hungary.2bisacsh1 aBeller, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackshaw, Gemma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlackshaw, Gemma, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHeighton, Luke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHowes, Geoffrey C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImrie, Nicola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuhn, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehninger, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMüller, Thomas, econtributor